<HEADLINE>
KMT TO HOLD PRESIDENTIAL PRIMARY IN LATE MAY
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei, Jan.  24 (CNA) 01/25/07  12:10:08 (By Han Nai-kuo)
</P>
<P>
The main opposition Kuomintang (KMT) will hold a presidential
primary May 26 to nominate the party's candidate in the 2008
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
According to an agenda approved by the KMT's Central Standing
Committee Wednesday, the KMT will announce the nomination process
schedule April 2.
</P>
<P>
KMT members interested in seeking the party's nomination for the
presidential election can pick up application forms April 3-5 and
register their candidacy between April 19 and 22.
</P>
<P>
An opinion poll will be conducted May 20-24 to determine the
approval ratings of the candidates, followed by the May 26
primary election in which only KMT members are eligible to vote.
</P>
<P>
According to regulations governing the KMT's primaries, in
determining who will be the party's candidate in an election,
support by KMT members accounts for 30 percent, while support by
voters as reflected by opinion polls is weighted at 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
The name of the winning presidential candidate will be publicized
late on May 26 and the nomination will be referred to the Central
Standing Committee for formal approval May 30.
</P>
<P>
The KMT will also announce on March 16 that KMT members who wish
to represent the party in contending for a legislative seat in
the year-end election should register their candidacy between
March 30 and April 2.
</P>
<P>
Would-be candidates will be divided into three groups and their
approval ratings determined through a primary election and three
opinion polls between mid-April and early June. The names of the
nominees will be announced June 9.
</P>
